  "JUSTIFICATION": "The provided regulation text describes the National Credit Union Administration's (NCUA) submission to the Office of Management and Budget for the renewal of two previously approved information collections. Both collections are categorized as Statutorily Required (SR) because they are directly necessary for the NCUA to fulfill its core statutory mandate under the Federal Credit Union Act (FCUA) to ensure the safety and soundness of federally insured credit unions.\n\n**Justification for SR Categorization:**\n\nThe **Federal Credit Union Act (12 U.S.C. § 1751 et seq.)** establishes the NCUA and grants it broad authority to regulate federal credit unions and to ensure the safety and soundness of the credit union system. Specifically, 12 U.S.C. § 1766(a) empowers the NCUA Board to prescribe rules and regulations necessary to carry out the provisions of the FCUA, including those related to safety and soundness. Furthermore, 12 U.S.C. § 1786 outlines the NCUA's examination and enforcement powers, which necessitate the collection of information to effectively monitor and supervise credit unions. The information collections described in this notice are integral to the NCUA's exercise of these fundamental statutory responsibilities.\n\n1.  **NCUA Template—Large Credit Union Data Collection (OMB Number: 3133-0209):** This collection is directly linked to 12 CFR part 702, subpart C, 'Capital Planning and Stress Testing,' which applies to federally insured credit unions with $10 billion or more in assets. The regulation text explicitly states that the data collected is 'needed to evaluate their internal assessments of capital adequacy and to ensure their capital resources are sufficient.' Capital adequacy and stress testing are fundamental components of prudential supervision, directly supporting the NCUA's statutory mandate to ensure the safety and soundness of large, complex credit unions. While the Dodd-Frank Act (specifically Section 165, 12 U.S.C. § 53